Super fast service which was perfect because we were in a rush. We had the channa masala salad bowl and lamb salad bowl. Both were flavourful and full of greens, just what we needed. The portion is huge, we could only eat a little over 1/2. The ingredients were nice and fresh. They kept the tables clean and there was enough seating for all the patrons. This is a great stop on the way to Navy Pier to avoid the lines ups and crowds once you get too close to the pier.

A little Indian surprise in downtown Chicago, Bombay puts it all in a wrap. Twice now, just quickly in and out of the City, I had a craving for something with curry/Indian foods flavor, and Bombay Wraps just popped up into view. This tonge I'm saving the location on my map!  Personally I recommend the Lamb Curry. You have a choice of extra toppings, but I just chose all (onion, lettuce and tomato-cucumber combo). Great flavor and fills a whole. But today I tried something extra. Potato Chips. Its crispy chips, fried while you wait, so tou get it hot, and off course with a little Indian spice sprinkled on top. Delightfully warm and delicious!  We'll be back!!!

Not bad experience at Bombay wraps on Wells street. They have different kinds of indian rolls in flaky bread called parathas. Perfect for a quick evening snack. Although portions are not huge they are adequate for the price around $5.50 a roll.  You can choose your toppings. they also have samosas masala chai and masala chips. Not a fancy sit down place. There are a few tables. Restroom is in basement and needs a key. They have a fountain machine and bottled soda as well.

Perhaps the first in Chicago area, fast and casual Indian restaurant that hits all the right notes through a limited but satisfying menu, whether you are looking to snack on something Indianish or wish a filling meal. Freshly prepared before you, the menu items are custom created to order. The staff is knowledgeable and ready to help make a decision. This has become my go to place when I am in a hurry.

It felt more like a Chipotle with some Indian filling/topping options.  Overall, I did enjoy my food and didn't feel too crammed. I'd at least check it out for yourself and see if it strikes a chord or not with you.  As for me, this is a very okay place.

Here is my recommendation for Indian vegetarians: get rice, lentil soup and mix them to get Sambar rice :-). Get their chickpea based item and you can have it as a side dish to go along with Sambar rice. I had this combo almost everyday for lunch, when I was on a recent visit to Chicago. Awesome. I'm not a big fan of mixing cooked food with raw vegetables and sauces. So, avoided their regular assembly line combo. I was a regular at Naansense before this; discovered Bombay Wraps this time around and I'm not complaining.

This place is one of those quick- let's grab lunch ones. Small white chairs and a bar style seating area, lots of light and a chance to people watch while you have your wrap.  The wrap itself wasnt incredible, I feel like it lacked one or two important masalas for the real bombay taste. I had the reshmi chicken which was shredded, not pieces of chicken, in a paratha. I also had the spicy chutney, which isnt all that spicy, so you can get a good dollop of it without your hair getting set on fire. Best part about the wrap was the onion mix, had an authentic street-food taste.  I would pop over once in a while when I'm craving indian street food real bad.
